# Node.js Security (OWASP)

When writing or changing TypeScript/Node code, follow [OWASP Node.js Security Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Nodejs_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html). Prefer secure defaults; do not introduce patterns the cheat sheet warns against.

## Asynchronous code and the event loop

- Prefer `async`/`await` with `try/catch`, or flat Promise chains with `.catch()`, over deep callback nesting so errors are not lost.
- Avoid blocking the event loop: no CPU-heavy sync work on hot paths; avoid `*Sync` fs/child_process APIs in request handlers (see project TypeScript rules).
- Order dependent async work so later steps run only after earlier ones complete (avoid races, e.g. auth in a callback vs. synchronous follow-up).

## HTTP requests and parsing

- Configure body/parser size limits appropriate to each route or content type; treat stated `Content-Type` as untrusted—validate payload shape/type before heavy parsing.
- Be aware Express-style parsers can turn repeated query keys into arrays or objects—validate types (string vs. array vs. object) before use.

## Input, output, and data exposure

- Validate input with allowlists or strict schemas; escape or sanitize HTML/JS when emitting user-controlled strings to HTML contexts (XSS).
- Apply authorization and least privilege; do not expose internal IDs or extra fields—return only fields the client needs (avoid mass assignment / over-fetching in APIs).
- Parameterize SQL; never concatenate user input into queries or shell commands.

## Dangerous APIs

- Do not use `eval`, `Function`, or `new Function` on user-influenced strings.
- Treat `child_process.exec` and shell interpolation as high risk—prefer `execFile`/`spawn` with argument arrays and validated inputs.
- Sanitize paths from users before `fs` operations; avoid directory traversal and unintended symlink following in security-sensitive paths.

## Errors and observability

- Do not return stack traces or internal error details to API clients; log details server-side.
- Handle `uncaughtException`/`unhandledRejection` per ops standards: log, release resources if safe, avoid continuing in a bad state.
- For `EventEmitter` and similar, attach `error` listeners so failures are not unhandled.
- Log for security and debugging without writing secrets, tokens, passwords, or full PII (follow [Logging Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Logging_Cheat_Sheet.html) ideas).

## HTTP server and sessions (when applicable)

- Set session cookies with `httpOnly`, `secure` (HTTPS), and appropriate `sameSite` for CSRF risk.
- Use security headers (e.g. Helmet or equivalent): CSP, HSTS where HTTPS, `X-Content-Type-Options`, frame controls; remove or avoid leaking `X-Powered-By`.
- For cookie-based state-changing requests, use established CSRF protection; do not rely on deprecated/unmaintained CSRF middleware.

## Abuse and availability

- Consider rate limiting or backoff on authentication and sensitive endpoints; avoid unbounded work per request (ReDoS: avoid vulnerable regex on user input; cap input size).

## Dependencies and runtime

- Prefer audited, maintained dependencies; avoid known-vulnerable patterns flagged by `npm audit` and team process.
- Use `"strict"` / TypeScript `strict` alignment with safe JS subset; avoid legacy foot-guns the cheat sheet calls out.

## Related project rules

- Complements `.cursor/rules/security-review.mdc` (reviewer lens) and `.cursor/rules/typescript-review.mdc` (TypeScript quality). When both apply, satisfy OWASP Node practices and project conventions together.
